      {
        "step": 52,
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Everything is wired and the sketch is loaded! Here's the full summary:\n\n---\n\n## 🔢 Button Counter — 0 to 9 on 7-Segment Display\n\n### Wiring Table\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Purpose |\n|-------------|-----------|---------|\n| **D2** | Button → one leg | Button input (INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| **GND** | Button → other leg | Button ground |\n| **D6** → R_A (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **a** (top) | Segment A |\n| **D7** → R_B (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **b** (top-right) | Segment B |\n| **D8** → R_C (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **c** (bot-right) | Segment C |\n| **D9** → R_D (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **d** (bottom) | Segment D |\n| **D10** → R_E (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **e** (bot-left) | Segment E |\n| **D11** → R_F (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **f** (top-left) | Segment F |\n| **D12** → R_G (220Ω) | 7-Seg pin **g** (middle) | Segment G |\n| **GND** | 7-Seg common cathode | Display ground |\n\n---\n\n### How It Works\n- Button uses **INPUT_PULLUP** — no external pull-up resistor needed\n- On each **falling edge** (press), `count` increments\n- After `9`, it wraps back to `0`\n- **50ms debounce delay** prevents double-counting\n\n---\n\n### ⚡ Power Budget\n\n| Load | Current |\n|------|---------|\n| Each lit segment (5V − 2V) / 220Ω | ~13.6 mA |\n| Max segments on at once (digit 8, all 7) | ~95 mA (7-seg display, 7 segments) |\n| Button (internal pull-up, ~50kΩ) | < 0.1 mA |\n| **Total max draw** | **~95 mA** |\n\n> ✅ Each pin sources ≤ 13.6 mA (well under the 20 mA limit). Total is within the Arduino Uno's 200 mA total port current. Safe to run from USB!"
      }
    ]
  },
